<div id=3D"outline-container-4" class=3D"outline-2">
<h2 id=3D"4">Miou, a simple scheduler for OCaml 5</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-4">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-miou-a-simple-scheduler=
-for-ocaml-5/12963/19">https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-miou-a-simple-schedu=
ler-for-ocaml-5/12963/19</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-orgbaadee6" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"orgbaadee6">Calascibetta Romain announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-orgbaadee6">
<p>
I am delighted to announce the release of <a href=3D"https://github.com/rob=
ur-coop/miou/releases/tag/v0.7.0">miou.0.7.0</a>. Whilst this release isn=
=E2=80=99t quite as impressive as previous ones, it now provides us with a =
pure OCaml implementation of SSH for our unikernels! This release notably i=
ntroduces <code>Miou.get</code>, which allows you to wait for and retrieve =
a task saved in an orphan: for this, we refer you to our documentation avai=
lable <a href=3D"https://docs.osau.re/local/miou/Miou/index.html#orphans">h=
ere</a>.
</p>

<p>
This release also strengthens our ecosystem in general: following <code>htt=
p</code>, <code>tls</code>, <code>tcp/ip</code>, <code>smtp</code>, <code>d=
ns</code> and <code>ntp</code>, we can now add <code>ssh</code> to the prot=
ocols available for our unikernels (as well as for OCaml applications in ge=
neral). It is largely thanks to @hannes=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://github=
.com/mirage/awa-ssh/pull/85">work</a> on migrating from <code>Cstruct.t</co=
de> (which we are now deprecating) to <code>string</code> (a process we beg=
an several years ago following observations of <a href=3D"https://blog.robu=
r.coop/articles/speeding-ec-string.html">performance issues with Cstruct.t<=
/a>) that we have managed to complete <code>mnet-ssh</code>.
</p>

<p>
And so, thanks to our work on <code>notty~/~nottui</code> (and [~lwd~](gith=
ub.com/let-def/lwd)), SSH support for unikernels, and one of our MirageOS r=
etreats, we have revived a project developed by @reynir: <a href=3D"https:/=
/github.com/reynir/banawa-chat/">banawa-chat</a>. It is a unikernel that of=
fers "a chat room for everyone" via SSH; you simply need to connect to it t=
o chat with others (a mini IRC) and it provides a TUI even though the unike=
rnel does not recognise the concept of a terminal! The project is available=
 <a href=3D"https://github.com/reynir/banawa-chat/pull/3">here</a> (and an =
<code>opam pin</code> is all you need to obtain <code>banawa.hvt</code>).
</p>


<div id=3D"org4e1c8f0" class=3D"figure">
<p><img src=3D"https://us1.discourse-cdn.com/flex020/uploads/ocaml/original=
/2X/e/e857f94d3f9f25767e79d2efccd893f2c4e2e044.webp" alt=3D"e857f94d3f9f257=
67e79d2efccd893f2c4e2e044.webp" width=3D"80%" />
</p>
</div>

<p>
This consolidation is now taking shape with the emergence of a few unikerne=
ls and tools, and we=E2=80=99re taking this opportunity to introduce you to=
 a few that are now available:
</p>
<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li>another older unikernel has just reappeared: <a href=3D"https://github.=
com/dinosaure/pasteur">pasteur</a> and its deployment <a href=3D"https://pa=
ste.osau.re/">https://paste.osau.re/</a>. It brings our efforts to <a href=
=3D"https://github.com/robur-coop/vif"><code>vif</code></a> and demonstrate=
s how to create a simple web application in the form of a unikernel.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/robur-coop/aussi"><code>aussi</code></a> =
is a small experimental project that can be used with Docker to deploy Solo=
5 unikernels quite simply (a simple <code>docker run</code> is enough now!)=
. However, we still recommend using <a href=3D"https://github.com/robur-coo=
p/albatross">albatross</a> for production deployment.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/robur-coop/chaos"><code>chaos</code></a> =
has finally crossed the Rubicon. Having started this project a year ago to =
experiment with our new workflow, this NTP server ("<a href=3D"https://chro=
ny-project.org/">Chrony</a>-style") is now available at <code>osau.re:123</=
code></li>
</ul>

<p>
We therefore continue to offer unikernels and actively use them in order to=
 improve them. As such, we would like to thank everyone who provides us wit=
h (any kind of) feedback on what we are developing, enabling us to collecti=
vely improve what our cooperative can offer the OCaml community (and, more =
broadly, the users of our unikernels). If you like what we do, you can supp=
ort us via a donation (<a href=3D"https://robur.coop/Donate">directly</a> o=
r via <a href=3D"https://github.com/sponsors/robur-coop">GitHub</a>). Happy=
 hacking!
</p>
</div>
</div>
